comment_data.body: This looks like debug that should go away.
It's an error, there's always an err. Well I mean the only time we emit it there's the err param, does something else emit error event to Client ?
hmm that's pretty useful for debugging precisely, gives more context than when the error is eventually caught, way later.

same answer, that gives context to the error
it basically isn't triggered unless there's something going wrong with nmp
Maybe it should be something else than a console.log though but I'm not sure what
If you want to add debugging information, use the `debug` function. I still think this one is out-of-place. Might as well add debug info in every single reader.
Nevermind, didn't see it was in the example.

For debugging info, the `debug` function should be used.

I still don't see what gain you have from logging every single number. Structures and Arrays could use some logging to get more context, but numbers ? A try/catch gets a small performance penalty because the function containing it cannot be optimized by v8, so it's a good idea to avoid putting it everywhere.

What would be a good idea is adding context to the Errors inside of Array and Structure readers/writers, so we know exactly which fieldInfo caused the trouble

Having something like https://github.com/roblabla/Protocols/blob/master/lib/protocols.js#L98-L105 would help to get more debug information here. The structural fields (Structure and Array) could use it to add context as to where the error occured in the fieldInfo chain.

also, same as before, `debug` is the function to use for debugging info

Hmm there was something wrong with numbers due to something else I think. Yeah you're right that one should be removed.

I turned the return {error:} to a throw Error in write because of https://github.com/PrismarineJS/node-minecraft-protocol/blob/4752a0d759d3828bd358bad389c1f587feffbfa7/src/transforms/serializer.js#L92 , so I guess that should be fixed one way or the other.

Adding context through that error object would do it indeed.

The problem with the debugging function is it displays every packet, kind of hard to find the interesting part in the ouput when enabled, but yeah I see your point.
Yeah okay, I'll fix it using something similar to what protocols does.

We could use [debug](https://github.com/visionmedia/debug) module to fix this. By making multiple debug modules for each part of the application, we could remove the spammy logging done.

It might also be a good idea to just remove the spam per-packet in general. I don't think it's actually useful, and can be turned back on when we need it ?
